# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: iso-26262-safety
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] There are four ASILs identified by the standard: ASIL A, ASIL B, ASIL C, ASIL D.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] ASIL D dictates the highest integrity requirements on the product and ASIL A the lowest.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Hazards that are identified as QM do not dictate any safety requirements.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Because of the reference to SIL and because the ASIL incorporate 4 levels of hazard with a 5th non-hazardous level, it is common in descriptions of ASIL to compare its levels to the SIL levels and DO-178C Design Assurance Levels, respectively.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] The determination of ASIL is the result of *hazard analysis and risk assessment*.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] In the context of ISO 26262, a hazard is assessed based on the relative impact of hazardous effects related to a system, as adjusted for relative likelihoods of the hazard manifesting those effects.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] In short, ASIL refers both to risk and to risk-dependent requirements (standard minimal risk treatment for a given risk).
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] illustrating the role of Exposure and Controllability in establishing relative probability, which is combined with Severity to form an expression of risk.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] The intervening levels are simply a range of intermediate degrees of hazard and degrees of assurance required.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] ISO 26262 "highly recommends" the use of semi-formal modeling languages for ASIL D designs (Stateflow and SysML provide examples of such languages).
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Executable validation using either prototyping or simulation is mandatory.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Loss of braking for only the rear wheels is less dangerous, so this hazard is associated with ASIL C.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Another example of a less critical function that warrants the ASIL C rating is cruise control.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] The use of semi-formal modeling languages is highly recommended for ASIL C designs.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] ASIL B examples are headlights and brake lights.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Modeling of the ASIL B design can rely on an informal languages.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] This and other differences requirements make the cost difference between C and B to be the largest step across all the ASILs.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] ASIL A is the lowest rating of the functional safety.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] A typical example are tail lights (non-braking).
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Less strict design walkthroughs can be used during the development (higher levels require more formal design inspections).
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Referring to "Quality Management", the QM level means that all assessed risks are tolerable from a safety perspective (even if the manufacturer might want to address them from a customer satisfaction perspective, for example make sure the vehicle starts).
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] So, safety assurance controls are unnecessary and standard quality management processes are sufficient for development.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Designing an entire system to the rigorous standards of the higher levels of ASIL can be unwieldy, so ISO 26262 allows "decomposition": redundant subcomponents, each designed to a lower ASIL level, can be combined into a higher ASIL level design using higher-level methodologies.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] The subcomponents used in this way shall contain features that would allow higher-level integration.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] The frequently used notation for an ASIL X-level component that can be used as a part of an ASIL Y-level system is X(Y).
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] For example, an A(B) component is designed at the ASIL A level of requirements, but is made to fit into ASIL B designs (this subcomponent is colloquially described as "B-ready").
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] ISO 26262 contains multiple examples of allowed decomposition scenarios, for example ASIL B = A(B) + A(B), i.e. two redundant B-ready ASIL A subcomponents can be combined into an ASIL B design.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Headlights provide a natural example of such decomposition: there are at least two of them, so they can be designed at ASIL A and combined into an ASIL B system as long as the combination is done properly (for example, it should not introduce a common point of failure).
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Given ASIL is a relatively recent development, discussions of ASIL often compare its levels to levels defined in other well-established safety or quality management systems.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] In particular, the ASIL are compared to the SIL risk reduction levels defined in IEC 61508 and the Design Assurance Levels used in the context of DO-178C and DO-254.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] While there are some similarities, it is important to also understand the differences.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] IEC 61508 defines a widely referenced Safety Integrity Level (SIL) classification.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Unlike other functional safety standards, ISO 26262 does not provide normative nor informative mapping of ASIL to SIL; while the two standards have similar processes for hazard assessment, ASIL and SIL are computed from different perspectives.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] That is, for a given Tolerable Risk, greater Risk requires more risk reduction, i.e., a smaller design target value for greater probability of dangerous failure.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] For a safety function operating in high demand or continuous mode of operation, SIL 1 is associated with a probability of dangerous failure limit of 10−5 per hour while SIL 4 is associated with a probability of dangerous failure rate limit of 10−9 per hour.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] In commercial publications, ASIL D has been illustrated to align with SIL 3 and ASIL A is compared to SIL 1.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] While it is more common to compare the ISO 26262 Levels D through QM to the Design Assurance Levels (DAL) A through E and ascribe those levels to DO-178C; these DAL are actually defined and applied through the definitions of SAE ARP4761 and SAE ARP4754.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Especially in terms of the management of vehicular hazards through a Safety Life Cycle, the scope of ISO 26262 is more comparable to the combined scope of SAE ARP4761 and SAE ARP4754.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Functional Hazard Assessment (FHA) is defined in ARP4761 and the DAL are defined in ARP4754.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] DO-178C and DO-254 define the design assurance objectives that must be accomplished for given DAL.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Unlike SIL, it is the case that both ASIL and DAL are statements measuring degree of hazard.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] DAL E is the ARP4754 equivalent of QM; in both classifications hazards are negligible and safety management is not required.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] At the other end, DAL A and ASIL D represent the highest levels of risk addressed by the respective standards, but they do not address the same level of hazard.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] While ASIL D encompasses at most the hazards of a loaded passenger van, DAL A includes the greater hazards of large aircraft loaded with fuel and passengers.
[src:iso-26262-safety/automotive-safety-integrity-level] Publications might illustrate ASIL D as equivalent to either DAL B, to DAL A, or as an intermediate level.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Sometimes FMEA is extended to FMECA(failure mode, effects, and criticality analysis) with Risk Priority Numbers (RPN) to indicate criticality.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] FMEA is an inductive reasoning (forward logic) single point of failure analysis and is a core task in reliability engineering, safety engineering and quality engineering.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] A successful FMEA activity helps identify potential failure modes based on experience with similar products and processes—or based on common physics of failure logic.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] It is widely used in development and manufacturing industries in various phases of the product life cycle.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] *Effects analysis* refers to studying the consequences of those failures on different system levels.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Functional analyses are needed as an input to determine correct failure modes, at all system levels, both for functional FMEA or piece-part (hardware) FMEA.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] An FMEA is used to structure mitigation for risk reduction based on either reducing the severity of the failure mode or effect, or on lowering the probability of failure, or both.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The FMEA is in principle a full inductive (forward logic) analysis; however the failure probability can only be estimated or reduced by understanding the *failure mechanism*.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Hence, FMEA may include information on causes of failure (deductive analysis) to reduce the possibility of occurrence by eliminating identified *(root) causes*.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The FME(C)A is a design tool used to systematically analyze postulated component failures and identify the resultant effects on system operations.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The analysis is sometimes characterized as consisting of two sub-analyses, the first being the failure modes and effects analysis (FMEA), and the second, the criticality analysis (CA).
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Successful development of an FMEA requires that the analyst include all significant failure modes for each contributing element or part in the system.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] FMEAs can be performed at the system, subsystem, assembly, subassembly or part level.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The FMECA should be a living document during development of a hardware design.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] It should be scheduled and completed concurrently with the design.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] If completed in a timely manner, the FMECA can help guide design decisions.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The usefulness of the FMECA as a design tool and in the decision-making process is dependent on the effectiveness and timeliness with which design problems are identified.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Timeliness is probably the most important consideration.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] In the extreme case, the FMECA would be of little value to the design decision process if the analysis is performed after the hardware is built.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] It starts at higher functional / system level.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] An FTA may use the basic failure mode FMEA records or an effect summary as one of its inputs (the basic events).
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Interface hazard analysis, human error analysis and others may be added for completion in scenario modelling.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The analysis should always be started by someone listing the functions that the design needs to fulfill.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Functions are the starting point of a well done FMEA, and using functions as baseline provides the best yield of an FMEA.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] After all, a design is only one possible solution to perform functions that need to be fulfilled.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] This way an FMEA can be done on concept designs as well as detail designs, on hardware as well as software, and no matter how complex the design.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] When performing a FMECA, interfacing hardware (or software) is first considered to be operating within specification.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] After that it can be extended by consequently using one of the 5 possible failure modes of one function of the interfacing hardware as a cause of failure for the design element under review.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] This gives the opportunity to make the design robust against function failure elsewhere in the system.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] In addition, each part failure postulated is considered to be the only failure in the system (i.e., it is a single failure analysis).
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] In addition to the FMEAs done on systems to evaluate the impact lower level failures have on system operation, several other FMEAs are done.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Special attention is paid to interfaces between systems and in fact at all functional interfaces.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The purpose of these FMEAs is to assure that irreversible physical and/or functional damage is not propagated across the interface as a result of failures in one of the interfacing units.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] These analyses are done to the piece part level for the circuits that directly interface with the other units.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The FMEA can be accomplished without a CA, but a CA requires that the FMEA has previously identified system level critical failures.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] When both steps are done, the total process is called an FMECA.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The ground rules of each FMEA include a set of project selected procedures; the assumptions on which the analysis is based; the hardware that has been included and excluded from the analysis; and the rationale for the exclusions.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The ground rules also describe the indenture level of the analysis (i.e. the level in the hierarchy of the part to the sub-system, sub-system to the system, etc.), the basic hardware status, and the criteria for system and mission success.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Every effort should be made to define all ground rules before the FMEA begins; however, the ground rules may be expanded and clarified as the analysis proceeds.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] All inputs (including software commands) to the item being analyzed are present and at nominal values.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] All consumables are present in sufficient quantities.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Major benefits derived from a properly implemented FMECA effort are as follows.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] A documented uniform method of assessing potential failure mechanisms, failure modes and their impact on system operation, resulting in a list of failure modes ranked according to the seriousness of their system impact and likelihood of occurrence.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Early identification of single failure points (SFPS) and system interface problems, which may be critical to mission success and/or safety.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] They also provide a method of verifying that switching between redundant elements is not jeopardized by postulated single failures.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] An effective method for evaluating the effect of proposed changes to the design and/or operational procedures on mission success and safety.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] A basis for in-flight troubleshooting procedures and for locating performance monitoring and fault-detection devices.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] From the above list, early identifications of SFPS, input to the troubleshooting procedure and locating of performance monitoring / fault detection devices are probably the most important benefits of the FMECA.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] In addition, the FMECA procedures are straightforward and allow orderly evaluation of the design.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Procedures for conducting FMECA were described in 1949 in US Armed Forces Military Procedures document MIL-P-1629, revised in 1980 as MIL-STD-1629A.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] By the early 1960s, contractors for the U.S.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) were using variations of FMECA or FMEA under a variety of names.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] NASA programs using FMEA variants included Apollo, Viking, Voyager, Magellan, Galileo, and Skylab.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The civil aviation industry was an early adopter of FMEA, with the Society for Automotive Engineers (SAE, an organization covering aviation and other transportation beyond just automotive, despite its name) publishing ARP926 in 1967.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] After two revisions, Aerospace Recommended Practice ARP926 has been replaced by ARP4761, which is now broadly used in civil aviation.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] During the 1970s, use of FMEA and related techniques spread to other industries.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] In 1971 NASA prepared a report for the U.S.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Geological Survey recommending the use of FMEA in assessment of offshore petroleum exploration.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Environmental Protection Agency report described the application of FMEA to wastewater treatment plants.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] FMEA as application for HACCP on the Apollo Space Program moved into the food industry in general.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The automotive industry began to use FMEA by the mid 1970s.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The Ford Motor Company introduced FMEA to the automotive industry for safety and regulatory consideration after the Pinto affair.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Ford applied the same approach to processes (PFMEA) to consider potential process induced failures prior to launching production.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] In 1993 the Automotive Industry Action Group (AIAG) first published an FMEA standard for the automotive industry.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The SAE first published related standard J1739 in 1994.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] This standard is also now in its fourth edition.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] In 2019 both method descriptions were replaced by the new AIAG / VDA FMEA handbook.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] It is a harmonization of the former FMEA standards of AIAG, VDA, SAE and other method descriptions.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] As of 2024, the AIAG / VDA FMEA Handbook is accepted by GM, Ford, Stellantis, Honda NA, BMW, Volkswagen Group, Mercedes-Benz Group AG (formerly Daimler AG), and Daimler Truck.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Although initially developed by the military, FMEA methodology is now extensively used in a variety of industries including semiconductor processing, food service, plastics, software, and healthcare.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Toyota has taken this one step further with its design review based on failure mode (DRBFM) approach.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The method is now supported by the American Society for Quality which provides detailed guides on applying the method.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The standard failure modes and effects analysis (FMEA) and failure modes, effects and criticality analysis (FMECA) procedures identify the product failure mechanisms, but may not model them without specialized software.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] This limits their applicability to provide a meaningful input to critical procedures such as virtual qualification, root cause analysis, accelerated test programs, and to remaining life assessment.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] To overcome the shortcomings of FMEA and FMECA a failure modes, mechanisms and effect analysis (FMMEA) has often been used.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] A variation of FMEA developed for functional safety applications is called Design Deviation and Mitigation Analysis (DDMA).[5] The DDMA variation adds information not normally included in a FMEA such as the automatic diagnostic mitigations, latent fault tests, and useful life.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] DDMA deletes RPN numbers as they are replaced by FMEDA results.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] For Ford specifically, these requirements had multiple-stage compliance deadlines of July and December of 2022.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The following covers some basic FMEA terminology.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The AP replaces the former risk matrix and RPN in the AIAG / VDA FMEA handbook 2019.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] It makes a statement about the need for additional improvement measures.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The loss of a function under stated conditions.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The specific manner or way by which a failure occurs in terms of failure of the part, component, function, equipment, subsystem, or system under investigation.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Depending on the type of FMEA performed, failure mode may be described at various levels of detail.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] A piece part FMEA will focus on detailed part or component failure modes (such as fully fractured axle or deformed axle, or electrical contact stuck open, stuck short, or intermittent).
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] A functional FMEA will focus on functional failure modes.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] These may be general (such as no function, over function, under function, intermittent function, or unintended function) or more detailed and specific to the equipment being analyzed.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] A PFMEA will focus on process failure modes (such as inserting the wrong drill bit).
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Defects in requirements, design, process, quality control, handling or part application, which are the underlying cause or sequence of causes that initiate a process (mechanism) that leads to a failure mode over a certain time.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] For example; "fatigue or corrosion of a structural beam" or "fretting corrosion in an electrical contact" is a failure mechanism and in itself (likely) not a failure mode.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The related failure mode (end state) is a "full fracture of structural beam" or "an open electrical contact".
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The initial cause might have been "Improper application of corrosion protection layer (paint)" and /or "(abnormal) vibration input from another (possibly failed) system".
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Immediate consequences of a failure on operation, or more generally on the needs for the customer / user that should be fulfilled by the function but now is not, or not fully, fulfilled.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] An identifier for system level and thereby item complexity.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Complexity increases as levels are closer to one.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The failure effect as it applies to the item under analysis.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The failure effect as it applies at the next higher indenture level.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The failure effect at the highest indenture level or total system.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The means of detection of the failure mode by maintainer, operator or built in detection system, including estimated dormancy period (if applicable).
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The likelihood of the failure occurring.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Severity (of the event) × probability (of the event occurring) × detection (probability that the event would not be detected before the user was aware of it).
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Severity considers the worst potential consequence of a failure, determined by the degree of injury, property damage, system damage and/or time lost to repair the failure.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Additional info, including the proposed mitigation or actions used to lower a risk or justify a risk level or scenario.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Severely reduced aircraft deceleration on ground and side drift.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Partial loss of runway position control.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] It is necessary to look at the cause of a failure mode and the likelihood of occurrence.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] This can be done by analysis, calculations / FEM, looking at similar items or processes and the failure modes that have been documented for them in the past.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] A failure cause is looked upon as a design weakness.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] All the potential causes for a failure mode should be identified and documented.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Examples of causes are: Human errors in handling, manufacturing induced faults, fatigue, creep, abrasive wear, erroneous algorithms, excessive voltage or improper operating conditions or use (depending on the used ground rules).
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] A failure mode may be given a *Probability Ranking* with a defined number of levels.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] This field is also often referred to as an *Occurrence Rating*.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] For a piece part FMEA, quantitative probability may be calculated from the results of a reliability prediction analysis and the failure mode ratios from a failure mode distribution catalog, such as RAC FMD-97.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] This method allows a quantitative FTA to use the FMEA results to verify that undesired events meet acceptable levels of risk.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Determine the Severity for the worst-case scenario adverse end effect (state).
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] It is convenient to write these effects down in terms of what the user might see or experience in terms of functional failures.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Examples of these end effects are: full loss of function x, degraded performance, functions in reversed mode, too late functioning, erratic functioning, etc.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Each end effect is given a Severity number (S) from, say, I (no effect) to V (catastrophic), based on cost and/or loss of life or quality of life.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] These numbers prioritize the failure modes (together with probability and detectability).
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Below a typical classification is given.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The means or method by which a failure is detected, isolated by operator and/or maintainer and the time it may take.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] This is important for maintainability control (availability of the system) and it is especially important for multiple failure scenarios.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] It should be made clear how the failure mode or cause can be discovered by an operator under normal system operation or if it can be discovered by the maintenance crew by some diagnostic action or automatic built in system test.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] A dormancy and/or latency period may be entered.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The average time that a failure mode may be undetected may be entered if known.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] If the undetected failure allows the system to remain in a *safe* / working state, a second failure situation should be explored to determine whether or not an indication will be evident to all *operators* and what corrective action they may or should take.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] This type of analysis is useful to determine how effective various test processes are at the detection of latent and dormant faults.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The method used to accomplish this involves an examination of the applicable failure modes to determine whether or not their effects are detected, and to determine the percentage of failure rate applicable to the failure modes which are detected.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The possibility that the detection means may itself fail latently should be accounted for in the coverage analysis as a limiting factor (i.e., coverage cannot be more reliable than the detection means availability).
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Inclusion of the detection coverage in the FMEA can lead to each individual failure that would have been one effect category now being a separate effect category due to the detection coverage possibilities.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Another way to include detection coverage is for the FTA to conservatively assume that no holes in coverage due to latent failure in the detection method affect detection of all failures assigned to the failure effect category of concern.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The FMEA can be revised if necessary for those cases where this conservative assumption does not allow the top event probability requirements to be met.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] After these three basic steps the Risk level may be provided.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Preliminary risk levels can be selected based on a risk matrix like that shown below, based on Mil.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The higher the risk level, the more justification and mitigation is needed to provide evidence and lower the risk to an acceptable level.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] High risk should be indicated to higher level management, who are responsible for final decision-making.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] A new FMEA variation, **Design Deviation and Mitigation Analysis (DDMA)**, has been introduced.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] This method adapts Functional Safety requirements to the Design FMEA process.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] This technique allows for the simultaneous collection of FMEDA information, leveraging functional safety engineering insights to streamline the FMEA.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The functional safety process largely replaces the need for traditional Risk Priority Numbers (RPN).
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] To facilitate FMEDA setup, the DDMA process also incorporates descriptions of automatic diagnostics (action taken, coverage) and evaluates the effectiveness of latent fault testing.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] While FMEA identifies important hazards in a system, its results may not be comprehensive and the approach has limitations.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] In the healthcare context, FMEA and other risk assessment methods, including SWIFT (Structured What If Technique) and retrospective approaches, have been found to have limited validity when used in isolation.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Challenges around scoping and organisational boundaries appear to be a major factor in this lack of validity.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] If used as a top-down tool, FMEA may only identify major failure modes in a system.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Fault tree analysis (FTA) is better suited for "top-down" analysis.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] When used as a bottom-up tool FMEA can augment or complement FTA and identify many more causes and failure modes resulting in top-level symptoms.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] It is not able to discover complex failure modes involving multiple failures within a subsystem, or to report expected failure intervals of particular failure modes up to the upper level subsystem or system.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Additionally, the multiplication of the severity, occurrence and detection rankings may result in rank reversals, where a less serious failure mode receives a higher RPN than a more serious failure mode.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The reason for this is that the rankings are ordinal scale numbers, and multiplication is not defined for ordinal numbers.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The ordinal rankings only say that one ranking is better or worse than another, but not by how much.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] For instance, a ranking of "2" may not be twice as severe as a ranking of "1", or an "8" may not be twice as severe as a "4", but multiplication treats them as though they are.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] See Level of measurement for further discussion.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Various solutions to this problems have been proposed, e.g., the use of fuzzy logic as an alternative to classic RPN model.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] In the new AIAG / VDA FMEA handbook (2019) the RPN approach was replaced by the AP (action priority) in the Supplemental FMEA for Monitoring and System Response (FMEA-MSR) method.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The FMEA worksheet is hard to produce, hard to understand and read, as well as hard to maintain.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The use of neural network techniques to cluster and visualise failure modes were suggested starting from 2010.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] An alternative approach is to combine the traditional FMEA table with a set of bow-tie diagrams.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The diagrams provide a visualisation of the chains of cause and effect, while the FMEA table provides the detailed information about specific events.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The software FMEA focuses on failure modes that originate in the software requirements, design, code or interfaces.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The software should not be treated as a "black box" in this analysis.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Instead a listing of root causes that historically lead to software failures should be considered instead.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The software FMEA is a design FMEA in that the goal is to identify missing, insufficient or incorrect design specifications before the code is written.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Probability is NOT computed from software failure rates for the simple reason that software failure rates measure the time between software failures of EVERY root cause as opposed to the time between a failure due to a single root cause.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Additionally, with software failures, the root causes will either be corrected or avoided when the failure occurs.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] So, time between a specific root cause has minimal value.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Medium severity failures that occur repeatedly can result in a very serious system failure.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] So the analyst must consider this when assessing severity.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Software failures aren't limited to a total loss of function.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] As per the IEEE 1633, if the software performs a function that is not correct as per the requirements, it is counted as a failure.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Compensating provisions don't necessarily mitigate the severity of a software failure.
[src:iso-26262-safety/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] That's because many software failures occur without warning and many cause damage before an operator can intervene.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] A safety system (often called a safety-related system) consists of one or more safety functions.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Functional safety is intrinsically end-to-end in scope in that it has to treat the function of a component or subsystem as part of the function of the entire automatic protection function of any system.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Thus, although functional safety standards focus on electrical, electronic, and programmable systems (E/E/PS), the end-to-end scope means that in practice, functional safety methods must extend to the non-E/E/PS parts of the system that the E/E/PS actuators, valves, motor controls or monitors.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Functional safety is achieved when every specified safety function is carried out and the level of performance required of each safety function is met.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Assessment of the risk-reduction required by the safety function, which will involve a safety integrity level (SIL) or performance level or other quantification assessment.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] A SIL (or PL, AgPL, ASIL) applies to an end-to-end safety function of the safety-related system, not just to a component or a part of the system.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Ensuring the safety function performs to the design intent, including under conditions of incorrect operator input and failure modes.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] This will involve having the design and lifecycle managed by qualified and competent engineers carrying out processes to a recognized functional safety standard.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] In Europe, that standard is IEC EN 61508, or one of the industry specific standards derived from IEC EN 61508, or for simple systems some other standard like ISO 13849.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Verification that the system meets the assigned SIL, ASIL, PL or agPL by determining the probability of dangerous failure, checking minimum levels of redundancy, and reviewing systematic capability (SC).
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] These three metrics have been called "the three barriers".
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Failure modes of a device are typically determined by failure mode and effects analysis of the system (FMEA).
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Failure probabilities for each failure mode are typically determined using failure mode, effects, and diagnostic analysis FMEDA.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Conduct functional safety audits to examine and assess the evidence that the appropriate safety lifecycle management techniques were applied consistently and thoroughly in the relevant lifecycle stages of product.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Neither safety nor functional safety can be determined without considering the system as a whole and the environment with which it interacts.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Functional safety is inherently end-to-end in scope.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Modern systems often have software intensively commanding and controlling safety-critical functions.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Therefore, software functionality and correct software behavior must be part of the Functional safety engineering effort to ensure acceptable safety risk at the system level.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Any claim of functional safety for a component, subsystem or system should be independently certified to one of the recognized functional safety standards.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] A certified product can then be claimed to be functionally safe to a particular safety integrity level or a performance level in a specific range of applications: the certificate and the assessment report is provided to the customers describing the scope and limits of performance.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Functional safety is a technically challenging field.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Certifications should be done by independent organizations with experience and strong technical depth (electronics, programmable electronics, mechanical, and probabilistic analysis).
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Functional safety certification is performed by accredited certification bodies (CB).
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Accreditation is awarded to a CB organization by an accreditation body (AB).
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] In the United States, the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) is the AB for functional safety accreditation.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] In the United Kingdom, the United Kingdom Accreditation Service (UKAS) provides functional safety accreditation.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] ABs are members of the International Accreditation Forum (IAF) for work in management systems, products, services, and personnel accreditation or the International Laboratory Accreditation Cooperation (ILAC) for laboratory testing accreditation.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] A multilateral recognition arrangement (MLA) between ABs will ensure global recognition of accredited CBs.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] IEC 61508 functional safety certification programs have been established by several global Certification Bodies.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Each has defined their own scheme based upon IEC 61508 and other functional safety standards.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] The scheme lists the referenced standards and specifies procedures which describes their test methods, surveillance audit policy, public documentation policies, and other specific aspects of their program.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Functional safety certification programs for IEC 61508 standards are being offered globally by several recognized CBs including Intertek, SGS, TÜV Rheinland, TÜV SÜD and UL.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] An important element of functional safety certification is on-going surveillance by the certification agency.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Most CB organizations have included surveillance audits in their scheme.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] The follow-up surveillance ensures that the product, sub-system, or system is still being manufactured in accordance with what was originally certified for functional safety.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Follow-up surveillance may occur at various frequencies depending on the certification body, but will typically look at the product's field failure history, hardware design changes, software changes, as well as the manufacturer's ongoing compliance of functional safety management systems.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] For military aerospace and defense systems MIL-STD-882E addresses functional hazard analyses (FHA) and determining which functions implemented in hardware and software are safety significant.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] The Functional safety focus is on ensuring safety critical functions and functional threads in the system, subsystem and software are analyzed and verified for correct behavior per safety requirements, including functional failure conditions and faults and appropriate mitigation in the design.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] These system safety principles underpinning functional safety were developed in the military, nuclear and aerospace industries, and then taken up by rail transport, process and control industries developing sector specific standards.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Functional safety standards are applied across all industry sectors dealing with safety critical requirements and are especially applicable anytime software commands, controls or monitors a safety-critical function.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Thousands of products and processes meet the standards based on IEC 61508: from bathroom showers, automotive safety products, sensors, actuators, diving equipment, Process Controllers and their integration to ships, aircraft and major plants.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] The US FAA have similar functional safety certification processes, in the form of ARP4761, US RTCA DO-178C for software and DO-254 for complex electronic hardware, which is applied throughout the aerospace industry.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Functional safety and design assurance on civil/commercial transport aircraft is documented in SAE ARP4754A as functional design assurance levels (FDALS).
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] The system FDALs drive the depth of engineering safety analysis.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] The level of rigor (LOR) or safety tasks performed to ensure acceptable risk are dependent upon the identification of specific functional failure condition and hazard severity relating to the safety-critical functions (SCF).
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] In many cases functional behavior in embedded software is thoroughly analyzed and tested to ensure the system functions as intended under credible fault and failure conditions.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Functional safety is becoming the normal focused approach on complex software intensive systems and highly integrated systems with safety consequences.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] The traditional software safety tasks and model based functional safety tasks are performed to provide objective safety evidence that the system functionality and safety features perform as intended in normal and off nominal failures.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] The entry point of functional safety begins early in the process by performing Functional Hazard Analyses (FHA)to identify hazards and risks and to influence the safety design requirements and functional allocation and decomposition to mitigate hazards.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] The behavior of the software and SCFs at the system level is a vital part of any functional safety effort.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Analyses and implementation results are documented in functional hazard assessments (FHA) or system safety assessments or safety cases.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Model-based functional safety processes are often used and required on highly integrated and complex software intensive systems to understand all of the many interactions and predicted behavior and to help in the safety verification and certification process.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] At Boeing, a Safety Review Board (SRB) is responsible for deciding only if an issue is or is not a safety issue.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] An SRB brings together multiple company subject-matter experts (SMEs) in many disciplines.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] The most knowledgeable SME presents the issue, assisted and guided by the Aviation Safety organization.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] Any vote for "safety" results in a board decision of "safety".
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] In the US, NASA developed an infrastructure for safety critical systems adopted widely by industry, both in North America and elsewhere, with a standard, supported by guidelines.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] The NASA standard and guidelines are built on ISO 12207, which is a software practice standard rather than a safety critical standard, hence the extensive nature of the documentation NASA has been obliged to add, compared to using a purpose designed standard such as IEC EN 61508.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] A certification process for systems developed in accord with the NASA guidelines exists.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] The automotive industry has developed ISO 26262 "Road Vehicles Functional Safety Standard" based on IEC 61508.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] The certification of those systems ensures the compliance with the relevant regulations and helps to protect the public.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] The ATEX Directive has also adopted a functional safety standard, it is BS EN 50495:2010 "Safety Devices Required for the Safe Functioning of Equipment with Respect to Explosion Risks" covers safety related devices such as purge controllers and Ex e motor circuit breakers.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] It is applied by notified bodies under the ATEX Directive.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] The standard ISO 26262 particularly addresses the automotive development cycle.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] It is a multi-part standard defining requirements and providing guidelines for achieving functional safety in E/E systems installed in series production passenger cars.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] ISO 26262 is considered a best-practice framework for achieving automotive functional safety.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] The compliance process usually takes time as employees need to be trained in order to develop the expected competencies.
[src:iso-26262-safety/functional-safety] The standard ISO 26262 is considered a best practice framework for achieving automotive functional safety.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] Functional safety features form an integral part of each automotive product development phase, ranging from the specification, to design, implementation, integration, verification, validation, and production release.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] The standard ISO 26262 is an adaptation of the Functional Safety standard IEC 61508 for Automotive Electric/Electronic Systems.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] ISO 26262 defines functional safety for automotive equipment applicable throughout the lifecycle of all automotive electronic and electrical safety-related systems.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] The first edition (ISO 26262:2011), published on 11 November 2011, was limited to electrical and/or electronic systems installed in "series production passenger cars" with a maximum gross weight of 3,500 kilograms (7,700 lb).
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] The second edition (ISO 26262:2018), published in December 2018, extended the scope from passenger cars to all road vehicles except mopeds.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] The standard aims to address possible hazards caused by the malfunctioning behaviour of electronic and electrical systems in vehicles.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] Although entitled "Road vehicles – Functional safety" the standard relates to the functional safety of Electrical and Electronic systems as well as that of systems as a whole or of their mechanical subsystems.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] ISO 26262 specifies a vocabulary (a Project Glossary) of terms, definitions, and abbreviations for application in all parts of the standard.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] A resulting *malfunction* that has a *hazardous* effect represents a loss of *functional safety*.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] is applied, that implements a function (or part of a function) at the vehicle level.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] is the highest identified object in the process and is thereby the starting point for product-specific safety development under this standard.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] (consisting of hardware parts and/or software units), a single hardware part or a single software unit — effectively, anything in a system that can be distinctly identified and manipulated.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] Discrepancy between a computed, observed or measured value or condition, and the true, specified or theoretically correct value or condition.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] caused by malfunctioning behaviour of Electrical/Electronic systems.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] ISO 26262 provides a standard for functional safety management for automotive applications, defining standards for overall organizational safety management as well as standards for a safety life cycle for the development and production of individual automotive products.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] and an operational situation of the vehicle with potential to lead to an accident if not controlled by timely driver action.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] as well as the validation and confirmation measures required by the standard to ensure accomplishment of that goal.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] and all levels of requirements decomposed from the safety goals down to and including the lowest level of functional and technical safety requirements allocated to hardware and software components.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] A comprehensive set of *hazardous events* are identified for the *item*.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] An *ASIL* is assigned to each *hazardous event*.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] A *safety goal* is determined for each *hazardous event*, inheriting the ASIL of the hazard.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] A vehicle level *functional safety concept* defines a *system architecture* to ensure the *safety goals*.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] *Safety goals* are refined into lower-level *safety requirements*.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] (In general, each safety requirement inherits the ASIL of its parent safety requirement/goal.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] The architectural components are then *developed* and *validated* in accord with the allocated safety (and functional) requirements.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] ISO 26262 defines objectives for integral processes that are supportive to the Safety Life Cycle processes, but are continuously active throughout all phases, and also defines additional considerations that support accomplishment of general process objectives.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] That is, each hazardous event is assessed in terms of severity of possible injuries within the context of the relative amount of time a vehicle is exposed to the possibility of the hazard happening as well as the relative likelihood that a typical driver can act to prevent the injury.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] At the beginning of the safety life cycle, hazard analysis and risk assessment is performed, resulting in assessment of ASIL to all identified hazardous events and safety goals.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] Risk Management recognizes that consideration of the severity of a possible injury is modified by how likely the injury is to happen; that is, for a given hazard, a hazardous event is considered a lower risk if it is less likely to happen.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] (C) (the relative likelihood that the driver can act to prevent the injury).
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] That is, *ASIL D* is the combination of S3, E4, and C3 classifications.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] *QM* refers to the standard's consideration that below *ASIL A*; there is no safety relevance and only standard Quality Management processes are required.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] These Severity, Exposure, and Control definitions are informative, not prescriptive, and effectively leave some room for subjective variation or discretion between various automakers and component suppliers.
[src:iso-26262-safety/iso-26262] In response, the Society for Automotive Safety Engineers (SAE) has issued *J2980 – Considerations for ISO26262 ASIL Hazard Classification* to provide more explicit guidance for assessing Exposure, Severity and Controllability for a given hazard.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] In functional safety, **safety integrity level** (**SIL**) is defined as the relative level of risk-reduction provided by a safety instrumented function (SIF), i.e. the measurement of the performance required of the SIF.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] In the functional safety standards based on the IEC 61508 standard, four SILs are defined, with SIL4 being the most dependable and SIL1 the least.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] The applicable SIL is determined based on a number of quantitative factors in combination with qualitative factors, such as risk assessments and safety lifecycle management.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] Other standards, however, may have different SIL number definitions.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] Assignment, or allocation of SIL is an exercise in risk analysis where the risk associated with a specific hazard, which is intended to be protected against by a SIF, is calculated without the beneficial risk reduction effect of the SIF.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] That unmitigated risk is then compared against a tolerable risk target.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] The difference between the unmitigated risk and the tolerable risk, if the unmitigated risk is higher than tolerable, must be addressed through risk reduction of provided by the SIF.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] This amount of required risk reduction is correlated with the SIL target.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] In essence, each order of magnitude of risk reduction that is required correlates with an increase in SIL, up to a maximum of SIL4.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] Should the risk assessment establish that the required SIL cannot be achieved by a SIL4 SIF, then alternative arrangements must be designed, such as non-instrumented safeguards (e.g, a pressure relief valve).
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] There are several methods used to assign a SIL.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] Of the methods presented above, LOPA is by far the most commonly used in large industrial facilities, such as for example chemical process plants.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] The assignment may be tested using both pragmatic and controllability approaches, applying industry guidance such as the one published by the UK HSE.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] SIL assignment processes that use the HSE guidance to ratify assignments developed from risk matrices have been certified to meet IEC 61508.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] There are several problems inherent in the use of safety integrity levels.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] According to IEC 61508, the SIL concept must be related to the dangerous failure rate of a system, not just its failure rate or the failure rate of a component part, such as the software.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] Definition of the dangerous failure modes by safety analysis is intrinsic to the proper determination of the failure rate.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] The International Electrotechnical Commission's (IEC) standard IEC 61508 defines SIL using requirements grouped into two broad categories: *hardware safety integrity* and *systematic safety integrity*.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] A device or system must meet the requirements for *both* categories to achieve a given SIL.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] The SIL requirements for hardware safety integrity are based on a probabilistic analysis of the device.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] In order to achieve a given SIL, the device must meet targets for the maximum probability of dangerous failure and a minimum safe failure fraction.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] The concept of 'dangerous failure' must be rigorously defined for the system in question, normally in the form of requirement constraints whose integrity is verified throughout system development.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] The actual targets required vary depending on the likelihood of a demand, the complexity of the device(s), and types of redundancy used.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] Hazards of a control system must be identified then analysed through risk analysis.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] Mitigation of these risks continues until their overall contribution to the hazard are considered acceptable.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] The tolerable level of these risks is specified as a safety requirement in the form of a target 'probability of a dangerous failure' in a given period of time, stated as a discrete SIL.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] Certification schemes, such as the CASS Scheme (Conformity Assessment of Safety-related Systems) are used to establish whether a device meets a particular SIL.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] Third parties that can provide certification include Bureau Veritas, CSA Group, TÜV Rheinland, TÜV SÜD and UL among others.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] The requirements of these schemes can be met either by establishing a rigorous development process, or by establishing that the device has sufficient operating history to argue that it has been proven in use.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] Electric and electronic devices can be certified for use in functional safety applications according to IEC 61508.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] There are a number of application-specific standards based on or adapted from IEC 61508, such as IEC 61511 for the process industry sector.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] This standard is used in the petrochemical and hazardous chemical industries, among others.
[src:iso-26262-safety/safety-integrity-level] The following standards use SIL as a measure of reliability and/or risk reduction.
